00:15:32.800 --> 00:15:36.190
of our surfaces-- web,
mobile, and especially TV--

00:15:36.190 --> 00:15:38.800
we're able to showcase
your app as a platform

00:15:38.800 --> 00:15:41.210
to watch that content.

00:15:41.210 --> 00:15:43.390
All you have to do as an
app developer is supply

00:15:43.390 --> 00:15:45.710
your content to
Google, and we can say,

00:15:45.710 --> 00:15:49.540
hey, this app has your content.

00:15:49.540 --> 00:15:52.820
We've updated that
to support live TV.

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:55.120
So now if you have a complex
electronic programming

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:57.340
guide and EPG, you
can submit that

00:15:57.340 --> 00:15:59.170
as part of your
Content Catalog, and we

00:15:59.170 --> 00:16:03.280
can surface this live TV content
across all of our surfaces.

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:05.887
In addition, we've updated
all of our documentation

00:16:05.887 --> 00:16:06.970
about these watch actions.

00:16:09.880 --> 00:16:14.240
Next, with search, we've also
added operator integrations.

00:16:14.240 --> 00:16:15.910
So if you're a TV
operator, you can

00:16:15.910 --> 00:16:20.260
have custom actions presented
to the user, such as DVR

00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:22.480
and record now.

00:16:22.480 --> 00:16:25.480
As a user, they can
still select more options

00:16:25.480 --> 00:16:28.110
and see your app that has
that content in search.

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:33.350
Lastly, I want to talk
about playback controls.

00:16:33.350 --> 00:16:36.820
We've made them even
easier with ExoPlayer.

00:16:36.820 --> 00:16:39.810
For playback controls, you
need to have a media session.

00:16:39.810 --> 00:16:42.040
What you're able to do now
is listen for callbacks

00:16:42.040 --> 00:16:43.940
from the user, such
as when they say,

00:16:43.940 --> 00:16:46.467
"Hey, Google, skip
forward five minutes."

00:16:46.467 --> 00:16:48.550
You end up getting these
callbacks through a media

00:16:48.550 --> 00:16:50.740
session callback.

00:16:50.740 --> 00:16:52.840
With ExoPlayer, we made
this easier by connecting

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:53.930
those two together.

00:16:53.930 --> 00:16:55.660
Let's dive further.

00:16:55.660 --> 00:16:57.880
Here, we're making a
media session, which just

00:16:57.880 --> 00:17:00.670
takes in a context in a tag.

00:17:00.670 --> 00:17:02.390
And then we set it to active.

00:17:02.390 --> 00:17:04.890
And if you have other things
you need to set, like the media

00:17:04.890 --> 00:17:06.910
session state or what
your player is doing,

00:17:06.910 --> 00:17:09.740
set that at this time as well.

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:12.069
Once you have an instance
to your media session,

00:17:12.069 --> 00:17:15.010
go ahead and find your
ExoPlayer instance.

00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:17.859
With those two, you can create
a MediaSession connector.

00:17:17.859 --> 00:17:19.420
This is a new
classroom and extension

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:22.573
library from ExoPlayer.

00:17:22.573 --> 00:17:24.490
Here we create a media
MediaSession connector,

00:17:24.490 --> 00:17:27.470
and we pass in that
media session instance.

00:17:27.470 --> 00:17:29.920
Later, we just call set
player, and we give it

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:31.840
the ExoPlayer instance.

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:33.670
The MediaSession
connector handles

00:17:33.670 --> 00:17:37.180
all of those playback controls
and all the callbacks for you.

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:40.053
If you do need to customize
it, it's super simple.

00:17:40.053 --> 00:17:42.220
You can add in all the extra
customization you need.

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:43.803
Say you have a music
playlist, and you

00:17:43.803 --> 00:17:45.880
want to customize
the queuing system,

00:17:45.880 --> 00:17:47.700
you can do that super
simple with this.

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:53.760
So to wrap that up, we've
implemented new live TV

00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:54.977
integrations.

00:17:54.977 --> 00:17:57.060
We've updated our documentation
and watch actions.

00:17:57.060 --> 00:18:01.805
And we made playback controls
even easier with ExoPlayer.

00:18:01.805 --> 00:18:03.180
Let's talk about
the home screen.

00:18:03.180 --> 00:18:05.013
This is where your
content can really shine.

00:18:09.010 --> 00:18:11.960
The first thing you notice
as a user is the app.

00:18:11.960 --> 00:18:14.860
The app shows up and represents
your branding and your content

00:18:14.860 --> 00:18:16.720
with a banner.

00:18:16.720 --> 00:18:18.490
We've discovered
some best practices,

00:18:18.490 --> 00:18:21.520
and we just want to
go over them quickly.

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:23.680
Here we have this
beautiful app Banner Best

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:26.500
Practice, my new favorite app.

00:18:26.500 --> 00:18:28.780
However, the banner matters.

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:31.780
In this case, we're
reusing the mobile icon,

00:18:31.780 --> 00:18:33.550
and we notice that
the app icon becomes

00:18:33.550 --> 00:18:36.100
very scrunched and hard to see.

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:37.780
This could lead to a
bad user experience

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:40.300
and not represent
your branding well.

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:41.920
On the opposite side
of the spectrum,

00:18:41.920 --> 00:18:43.690
here we have an image
that's too large,

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:46.690
and gets scaled,
and might be blurry.

00:18:46.690 --> 00:18:49.570
You really want to have a
banner that's 320 by 180.

00:18:49.570 --> 00:18:53.560
You also want to put that
banner in the XHDPI folder.

00:18:53.560 --> 00:18:55.180
If you put it in
just drawable, it's

00:18:55.180 --> 00:18:57.190
going to be recognized
as an MDPI folder,

00:18:57.190 --> 00:19:00.595
and this could lead to scaling
and blurriness with your image.

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:06.613
Also note, we do reuse your
banner in certain contexts.

00:19:06.613 --> 00:19:08.030
Depending where
the user is and we

00:19:08.030 --> 00:19:09.680
need to represent
your branding, we

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:11.540
reuse that banner
across the home screen.

00:19:15.502 --> 00:19:17.960
So the home screen-- real fast
time to tie in to what Anwar

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:19.040
talked about earlier--

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:20.900
really comprises
of three things.

00:19:20.900 --> 00:19:23.570
Channels-- these are
rows that you can

00:19:23.570 --> 00:19:26.490
surface content to the user.

00:19:26.490 --> 00:19:29.968
In addition, there's also a play
next row that's system managed,

00:19:29.968 --> 00:19:31.760
and you can add content
there for the users

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:33.620
to quickly hop back in.

00:19:33.620 --> 00:19:35.870
Finally, you can
have video previews.

00:19:35.870 --> 00:19:37.880
For example, here we
have an immersive preview

00:19:37.880 --> 00:19:38.840
from Red Bull.

00:19:38.840 --> 00:19:40.910
And we've seen increased
engagement from apps

00:19:40.910 --> 00:19:44.030
that support video previews.

00:19:44.030 --> 00:19:46.010
How does this work
under the covers?

00:19:46.010 --> 00:19:47.930
Your app is going to
talk to the launcher

00:19:47.930 --> 00:19:49.430
through a content provider.

00:19:49.430 --> 00:19:52.400
You can send over any
data, games, music, video

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:54.210
that your app has,
and the launcher

00:19:54.210 --> 00:19:57.885
is going to store that in
the TV provider database.

00:19:57.885 --> 00:19:59.510
Since we're using
the content provider,

00:19:59.510 --> 00:20:01.520
we're able to do some
optimizations that

00:20:01.520 --> 00:20:03.890
are pretty cool.

00:20:03.890 --> 00:20:05.910
If you used the content
provider before,

00:20:05.910 --> 00:20:08.810
you may be use to content
provider operations.

00:20:08.810 --> 00:20:10.940
We can optimize all
of these operations

00:20:10.940 --> 00:20:13.160
when we go to update the
home screen by doing this

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:15.030
all in bulk.

00:20:15.030 --> 00:20:17.480
So for example, we make
a call to our back end,

00:20:17.480 --> 00:20:18.980
and we get a list
of content that we

00:20:18.980 --> 00:20:20.330
need to add to the home screen.

00:20:20.330 --> 00:20:22.700
We can look through that
content and look through what's

00:20:22.700 --> 00:20:25.460
in our channel and say, hey,
here's a bunch of new content

00:20:25.460 --> 00:20:29.210
that we need to add and
create a new operation to add

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:30.710
that content.

00:20:30.710 --> 00:20:32.390
This creates an
operation that we can

00:20:32.390 --> 00:20:35.670
add to our list of operations.

00:20:35.670 --> 00:20:38.760
Or vice versa, we can also say
these pieces of content need

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:42.630
to be removed and create
delete operations.

00:20:42.630 --> 00:20:45.180
Finally, whatever is left, we
should just update and make

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:48.150
a bunch of update operations.

00:20:48.150 --> 00:20:50.800
When we're done, we can
apply all of these in batch.

00:20:50.800 --> 00:20:52.497
This allows us to
have one transaction

00:20:52.497 --> 00:20:54.580
and optimize the performance
with the home screen.

00:20:57.260 --> 00:20:59.350
I'm also happy to announce
that with AndroidX, we

00:20:59.350 --> 00:21:00.662
made this easier for you.

00:21:00.662 --> 00:21:02.620
You don't have to worry
about content providers

00:21:02.620 --> 00:21:04.210
when using AndroidX.

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:05.680
Let's take a look.

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:08.320
Here we have a preview
channel helper.

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:11.680
And in this helper, you can
add all the metadata you need.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:14.560
And lastly, you
can add the logo.

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:17.320
The logo should be
an 80 by 80 picture.

00:21:17.320 --> 00:21:20.057
And as the system, we're
going to apply a mask

00:21:20.057 --> 00:21:22.390
and show a final image that
might be different then what

00:21:22.390 --> 00:21:23.530
you supplied.

00:21:23.530 --> 00:21:25.540
Think of it like adaptive
icons for a mobile,

00:21:25.540 --> 00:21:27.190
but not quite the same.

00:21:27.190 --> 00:21:30.070
What matters most is that you
supply an 80 by 80 image for us

00:21:30.070 --> 00:21:32.910
to use.

00:21:32.910 --> 00:21:35.640
Once you have your channel,
you just add publish channel,

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:37.980
and this does everything as
one transaction for you--

00:21:37.980 --> 00:21:40.277
no more content provider.

00:21:40.277 --> 00:21:42.360
Once you get the channel
ID, you should store this

00:21:42.360 --> 00:21:43.740
for synchronizing
later where you

00:21:43.740 --> 00:21:46.032
might want to use those batch
operations from a content

00:21:46.032 --> 00:21:48.380
provider.

00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:50.360
Next, I want to talk
about the play next row.

00:21:50.360 --> 00:21:52.943
Over the past couple of years,
I've worked with a lot of apps,

00:21:52.943 --> 00:21:54.950
and TV shows really shine
on the play next row.

00:21:57.730 --> 00:21:59.680
This is an example
from the DC universe

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:01.960
app, where they have
strong indications

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:05.080
to watch "Young Justice."

00:22:05.080 --> 00:22:07.210
As a user, you could be
halfway through a show.

00:22:07.210 --> 00:22:09.685
Here we're 10 minutes
into a 21-minute episode,

00:22:09.685 --> 00:22:10.923
and then you leave.

00:22:10.923 --> 00:22:12.340
And when you leave,
as an app, you

00:22:12.340 --> 00:22:15.580
can add strong notes
and UI indicators, "Hey,

00:22:15.580 --> 00:22:17.600
you're halfway through."

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:20.770
In addition, you can add this
content to the play next row.

00:22:23.480 --> 00:22:25.130
One thing we noticed
is that there's

00:22:25.130 --> 00:22:28.050
a piece of metadata called
last engagement time.

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:29.180
This sounds pretty trivial.

00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:32.120
It represents the last
timestamp a user or an app

00:22:32.120 --> 00:22:35.870
has interacted with
that piece of content.

00:22:35.870 --> 00:22:38.690
Here for example, when
the user pauses the show,

00:22:38.690 --> 00:22:42.920
that should be the timestamp
for last engagement time.

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:45.800
When the user goes back in and
they finish watching the show

00:22:45.800 --> 00:22:48.290
and they see the credits,
this is a great time

00:22:48.290 --> 00:22:51.320
to add a next episode
to the play next row.

00:22:54.500 --> 00:22:57.510
Here DC adds the next episode.

00:22:57.510 --> 00:23:00.345
We're able to give strong
visual indicators to the user,

00:23:00.345 --> 00:23:01.470
"This' is the next episode.

00:23:01.470 --> 00:23:03.310
Here's where you left off."

00:23:03.310 --> 00:23:06.210
But the timestamp for last
engagement time should change.

00:23:06.210 --> 00:23:08.580
This should be the time
the credits came up.

00:23:08.580 --> 00:23:10.260
This is technically
the last time

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:12.510
the user has interacted
with that season.

00:23:12.510 --> 00:23:14.310
If you think of
that as a season,

00:23:14.310 --> 00:23:15.900
last engagement time
makes more sense

00:23:15.900 --> 00:23:19.440
since they haven't interacted
with the next episode.

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:22.730
The last part of the lifecycle
of a TV show is new episode.

00:23:22.730 --> 00:23:25.400
So a new piece of content
for "Young Justice"

00:23:25.400 --> 00:23:26.560
hasn't come out yet.

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:28.590
It'll be aired at a later date.

00:23:28.590 --> 00:23:31.130
So user has not
interacted with that yet.

00:23:31.130 --> 00:23:33.500
You can still add that
to the home screen

00:23:33.500 --> 00:23:36.080
and set the last
engagement time to the time

00:23:36.080 --> 00:23:38.240
when the episode is aired.

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:40.580
The launcher sees that
that time is in the future

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:45.200
and will handle the
content accordingly.

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:48.790
There's a bunch of pros and
cons and dos and don'ts.

00:23:48.790 --> 00:23:50.590
The key rule of
thumb is if a user

00:23:50.590 --> 00:23:52.600
interacts with a piece
of content, that's

00:23:52.600 --> 00:23:53.920
fair game for the home screen.

00:23:58.590 --> 00:24:01.320
Lastly, I want to talk about how
to make your app more friendly

00:24:01.320 --> 00:24:03.240
and be prepared for
when these changes come

00:24:03.240 --> 00:24:06.483
for commerce later, such
as Anwar talked about.

00:24:06.483 --> 00:24:08.400
Mainly, it comes down
to distributing your app

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:09.760
in the Play Store.

00:24:09.760 --> 00:24:11.360
You need to do a few things.

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:13.320
One, in your manifest
file, declare that you

00:24:13.320 --> 00:24:15.000
use the lean back feature.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.430
Two, make sure you have
the lean back intent

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:19.990
to filter for your
main activity.

00:24:19.990 --> 00:24:22.890
The last thing you need to do is
when you're in your Play Store

00:24:22.890 --> 00:24:25.530
listing, go to pricing
and distribution

00:24:25.530 --> 00:24:27.750
and select this check box.

00:24:27.750 --> 00:24:30.900
What this does is this enables
a process that sends your app

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:32.525
to the Play Store review team.

00:24:32.525 --> 00:24:34.650
They're going to review
your app for simple things,

00:24:34.650 --> 00:24:39.105
like D-pad support, app
crashes, and gives you a report

00:24:39.105 --> 00:24:40.830
if it doesn't support this.

00:24:40.830 --> 00:24:43.140
This helps ensure that we
have a basic bar of quality

00:24:43.140 --> 00:24:45.030
for the Android TV apps.

00:24:45.030 --> 00:24:46.710
We have documented
what those checks

00:24:46.710 --> 00:24:48.810
are on developer.Android.com.

00:24:52.580 --> 00:24:54.710
By having your app on
the Play Store, when

00:24:54.710 --> 00:24:56.420
we support features
like subscriber

00:24:56.420 --> 00:24:58.858
install later this year, you're
already ahead of the game

00:24:58.858 --> 00:25:00.275
and can start
making money faster.

00:25:03.030 --> 00:25:06.470
So in conclusion then, the three
things we've been focusing on

00:25:06.470 --> 00:25:08.180
are making your app
easier to integrate

00:25:08.180 --> 00:25:12.620
with the Assistant, such as
with live TV and watch actions.

00:25:12.620 --> 00:25:15.560
Having your content really shine
on the home screen requires

00:25:15.560 --> 00:25:18.890
a little effort with your banner
and making channels easier--

00:25:18.890 --> 00:25:21.440
channels and play next
easier for your app.

00:25:21.440 --> 00:25:24.200
And lastly with the Play
Store, making sure you opt in

00:25:24.200 --> 00:25:28.272
will enable your app to be
discovered on Android TVs.

