00:38:06.010 --> 00:38:10.310
OK, so next one is Multi-Live.

00:38:10.310 --> 00:38:15.630
Multi-Live is pushing the limits
of the Android TV platform.

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:20.830
So in this example, you have
four instances of ExoPlayer,

00:38:20.830 --> 00:38:22.670
and we have to tweak
a lot of things

00:38:22.670 --> 00:38:25.165
to make the playback
very seamlessly.

00:38:25.165 --> 00:38:28.910
These animation are powered
by the control set animation.

00:38:28.910 --> 00:38:32.415
We also have to synchronize
all the other [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:32.415 --> 00:38:35.420
of all the [INAUDIBLE]
player at the same time.

00:38:35.420 --> 00:38:40.100
And we have to know where the
adaption of the player which

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:43.490
are not in front of the users.

00:38:43.490 --> 00:38:47.105
And higher up, the
one which is at the--

00:38:47.105 --> 00:38:47.980
which is [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:47.980 --> 00:38:50.220
Sorry.

00:38:50.220 --> 00:38:55.610
So the caveat is that not any
devices can handle Multi-Live,

00:38:55.610 --> 00:39:00.350
and we had to determine
which one is capable or not.

00:39:00.350 --> 00:39:09.230
So ExoPlayer gives you a little
tool on the media [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:09.230 --> 00:39:15.350
to give you how many
instances a device can handle.

00:39:15.350 --> 00:39:20.120
But do not trust it at 100%
because, first, a device

00:39:20.120 --> 00:39:21.770
can lie to you.

00:39:21.770 --> 00:39:26.930
And also you may have another
application using any codecs

00:39:26.930 --> 00:39:28.800
behind your application.

00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:33.830
So it's a bit
confusing, but it's also

00:39:33.830 --> 00:39:39.350
a nice way to the determine
how many instances a device can

00:39:39.350 --> 00:39:41.240
handle.

